    _article_doc(article='36', title='Definition of the State for Directive Principles', focus='This provision belongs to the Directive Principles or structural governance provisions and guides legislation, policy, and constitutional interpretation. Even where non-justiciable, it shapes how courts understand welfare, reasonableness, and the social purpose of State action.', consequence='Most of these provisions are not directly enforceable like Fundamental Rights, but they strongly influence legislation, constitutional balancing, public interest litigation, and the validity of welfare-oriented regulation. Article 51A, though non-justiciable, is often invoked to support civic responsibilities and environmental obligations.', related='Part III, welfare legislation, labour and education statutes, environmental law, reservation policy, and governance reforms', case_law='Courts have used Directive Principles to expand Article 21, justify social welfare laws, and harmonise rights with social justice. Fundamental duties are sometimes cited in environmental, education, and civic order cases.', procedure='advocates often use these provisions to defend reform legislation, support public interest claims, or interpret ambiguous statutes in favour of welfare, dignity, and constitutional morality'),
