    _article_doc(article='72', title='Pardoning Power of the President', focus='This article forms part of the institutional design of the higher judiciary or constitutional government. It allocates power, jurisdiction, or responsibility and is often interpreted to preserve separation of powers, independence, and constitutional accountability.', consequence='The practical consequence lies in allocation and limitation of constitutional power. The article may validate governmental action if used properly or expose it to review if exercised for collateral, arbitrary, or constitutionally impermissible reasons.', related='Separation of powers, parliamentary procedure, executive accountability, and judicial review', case_law='Key cases include ordinance review decisions, mercy petition jurisprudence, and privilege cases testing the limits of institutional autonomy against constitutional supremacy.', procedure='challenges usually focus on scope of power, procedural prerequisites, mala fides, justiciability, and whether constitutional conventions or binding limits were respected'),
